sentence_chunk: VIATOURS FICTIONAL COMPANY PDF FILE  Viatours is a fictional company, born out of Nikolas Tuz’s full-stack development project. Nikolas Tuz, a seasoned Software Developer, specializes in building and designing custom full-stack e-commerce applications. The Viatours Project is an advanced e-commerce platform focused on selling tour tickets, specifically tailored to U. S. customers. All meeting points for the tours are located within the United States, providing a streamlined and localized experience. The project was developed using Next.js, a powerful full-stack framework based on React, enabling seamless performance and scalability. "I used TypeScript as the core language for building this application," says Nikolas, emphasizing the project's focus on type safety and maintainability. For the database, a highly scalable MongoDB solution was chosen to ensure optimal performance for handling dynamic tour data and customer bookings. The Viatours Full-Stack Project includes more than 20 distinct pages, each contributing to the seamless user experience. Some of the key pages are: 1. Home Page – The entry point of the site, showcasing featured tours and promotions. (

2. Search Tours Page – Allows users to browse and filter available tours based on their preferences. (http://localhost:3000/tours) 3. Tour Details Page – Provides in-depth information about individual tours. (http://localhost:3000/tours/<tourId>) 4. Sign In – The login page for existing users. (http://localhost:3000/login) 5. Sign Up – Registration page for new users. (http://localhost:3000/register) 6. Forgot Password – A recovery page for users who need to reset their password. (

http://localhost:3000/login/forgot-password) 7. User Profile Page – A personalized dashboard where users can manage their account details. (http://localhost:3000/account- settings?page=profile) 8. User Notifications – Displays updates and notifications for the user. (http://localhost:3000/account-settings?page=notifications) 9. User Wishlist – Allows users to save and view tours they are interested in. (http://localhost:3000/account-settings?page=wishlist) 10. User Saved Articles – A collection of articles the user has bookmarked. (http://localhost:3000/account-settings?page=saved- articles) 11. User Tour Purchases – A summary of the user’s past and current tour purchases.

12. Delete Account – A page for users to permanently delete their account. (http://localhost:3000/account-settings?page=delete-account) 13. Tour Articles – A section featuring articles related to various tours. (http://localhost:3000/articles) 14. Tour Article Description – Displays detailed information for individual articles. (http://localhost:3000/articles/<articleID>) 15. Proceed with Order Page – The checkout page for finalizing tour purchases. 16. Thanks for Purchase Page – A confirmation page displayed after a successful purchase.

(http://localhost:3000/thanks-for- purchase) 17. Track Order Page – Allows users to track the status of their tour orders. (http://localhost:3000/track-order) 18. Track Order Details – Provides detailed information on a specific order’s progress. (http://localhost:3000/track-order) 19. 404 Page – Displayed when a user navigates to a page that doesn’t exist. 20. 500 Error Page – Shown when there’s an internal server error. 21. ChatBot AI Agent UI – The interface for interacting with the AI-powered chatbot.
22. A lot of Banners – Various banners designed for marketing purposes (not used in production). 23. And more… – Additional pages designed to enhance the overall user experience.

Each page in the Viatours Project is designed with functionality that aligns with its specific purpose. I'll detail some of the key features. Loading States and Skeletons One of the primary concepts implemented is the use of Skeletons for handling loading states. Instead of traditional spinners (though they are used sparingly), I opted for skeleton screens that mimic the layout of the actual page or component, which is waiting for data to be fetched from the MongoDB server. This approach offers a smoother and more intuitive experience for users. For instance, when a user reaches the "Proceed with Order" page, they initially see skeleton placeholders that resemble the actual layout until the real data loads. User-Friendly, Fast, and Feature-Rich The core goal of the Viatours Tourism Full Stack Project was to create an application that is fast, efficient, user-friendly, and rich in features. I believe these goals were successfully achieved. From a technical standpoint, the project is designed to ensure that users can browse, search, and purchase tour tickets with ease and speed. Payment Integration with Stripe For the payment gateway, I integrated Stripe Payments, providing a secure and seamless payment experience for users during the checkout process.

To reiterate, Viatours is not a real-world platform for purchasing tour tickets; rather, it is my portfolio project—a personal and academic showcase of my skills as a developer. "This is my portfolio project," says Nikolas Tuz. Details and Thorough Form Validation In the Viatours Project, every form—whether it’s for submitting comments, placing an order, updating user information, or managing the wishlist and saved articles—undergoes rigorous validation. Each input is carefully validated, ensuring data integrity and preventing errors. Validation is performed on both the client side and server side to guarantee a seamless and secure user experience. Client-side validation offers immediate feedback to users, while server-side validation adds an additional layer of security, ensuring that all inputs are accurate and safe before being processed. Tickets Each tour in the Viatours Project is packed with details, and the ticketing system is designed to cater to different age groups. Every ticket offers three distinct categories: 1. Adults – Priced at the highest tier. 2.

Users can select the ticket type that best suits their needs. Additionally, they can choose from available times for each tour and pick a calendar date that fits their schedule. Beyond the basic ticket selection, users also have the flexibility to enhance their experience by adding services. They can opt for “Add service per booking,” which applies the selected service to the entire group, or “Add service per person,” which applies the service individually to each participant. Add Service per Booking  This option applies the service or feature to the entire booking, regardless of how many people are in the group.  Example: If you're booking a tour for a family of four, and you select an additional service like "Private Transfer" or "Guided Tour," this service is applied to the entire group, not each individual.  Common services: Private car transfers, group photo packages, tour guide fees, etc. 2. Add Service per Person  This option applies the service or feature to each person in the booking.  Example: If the family of four wants to add a service like "Lunch" or "Travel Insurance," and you select "per person," this service will be applied individually to each traveler.

These options allow users to tailor their booking experience by adding services based on their needs and preferences, either for the entire group or for each person individually. Proceed with Payment Page After the user selects the number of tickets, time, and preferred travel date, they are redirected to the Proceed with Payment page. This page is divided into three interrelated sections: 1. Contact Details 2. Activity Details 3. Payment 1. Contact Details In this section, the user is prompted to enter their email, phone number, first name, and last name. There is also an option to subscribe to Viatours' newsletter through a checkbox labeled: "Get emails with special offers, inspiration, tips, and other updates from Viatours. You can unsubscribe at any time." If the user selects this checkbox and the order is successfully placed, their email is upserted into the newsletter MongoDB collection.
To ensure security, if an unauthenticated user tries to enter an email that already exists in the database, the form will prompt them to log in first, as

part of the thorough validation process. Each input is meticulously validated on both the client and server sides. 2. Activity Details Once the Contact Details section is validated, the Activity Details section becomes active. Here, the user can review the selected tour, including:  Tour image  Tour name  Selected date  Number of tickets  Total price Additionally, the user must enter the first and last names of each traveler. The meeting point for the tour is displayed, and an optional input field is provided for Special Requirements. The user also selects the Tour Language from the available options. 3. Payment After the Activity Details are completed correctly, the Payment section opens. Here, the user can enter their card credentials, processed through Stripe.

Since Viatours is a fictional project, the Stripe account is set to Test Mode, and users are encouraged to use the dummy card number 4242 4242 4242 4242, along with any credentials, to simulate a successful payment.

Once the payment is processed successfully, the user is redirected to the Thanks for Purchase page. The first thing they see is a skeleton loader, followed by the actual order details. To enhance the user experience, the order ID is easily copyable with a single click. This page features two action buttons: 1. Keep Shopping 2. Track Order  The Keep Shopping button redirects the user back to the Search Tours page, allowing them to continue exploring other tours.  The Track Order button has a more specific function. If the user is authenticated (with an active session), clicking this button redirects them to their Account Settings page, specifically to the Tour Purchases section, at the following URL: http://localhost:3000/account-settings?page=tour-purchases. This ensures that only authenticated users can access their order tracking details securely. I’ve rented the viatours.net for 1 year domain to enable email functionality, allowing me to send order confirmation emails directly to users, not only to my own inbox.

When a purchase is completed successfully, the user receives an email with all the essential details of their order, including the tour name, tickets purchased, total amount, and any special instructions. This ensures users have a clear record of their purchase right in their inbox.

Tracking Orders Users have two primary ways to track their order, depending on their authentication status: 1. Authenticated Users: If the user was logged in while making the purchase, they can track their order through their Account Settings page. The specific URL for tracking is: http://localhost:3000/account-settings?page=tour-purchases. This page provides a personalized overview of all previous purchases, allowing the user to easily view and manage their orders. 2. Unauthenticated Users: Users who were not logged in can track their order by visiting the Track Order page at: http://localhost:3000/track-order. This page is accessible to anyone with a valid order ID, offering a quick way to retrieve order information without requiring a login. Track Order Page Layout The Track Order page consists of two main components: 1. Enter Order ID Page Upon landing on this page, users are prompted to enter their Order ID. This form is thoroughly validated to ensure only valid order IDs are accepted.

2. Order Details Page Once a valid Order ID is submitted, the user is shown a detailed overview of their order. This section contains: o Order Status – Whether the order is confirmed, pending, or completed. o Order ID – A unique identifier for the order. o Tour Title – The name of the tour that was booked. o Tickets – The number of tickets purchased, broken down by category (Adults, Youth, Children). o Refund Availability – Indicates if a refund can still be requested. o Cancellation Availability – Shows whether the tour booking can be canceled. o Order Made By – Displays the name of the person who placed the order. o Created Date – The date when the order was made.

o Meeting Point – This section includes the location where the tour begins, along with a Google Maps button. Clicking this button redirects the user to Google Maps, showing the exact meeting location for the tour. The most critical part of this page is the Actions Section. If the order qualifies for cancellation or refund, the user is presented with options to initiate either action. This makes it simple for users to manage their bookings, request a cancellation, or apply for a refund with just a few clicks.

Requesting a Refund or Cancellation When users need to request a refund or cancellation, they have two different pathways depending on where they are: 1. Track Order Page If users are on the Track Order page and wish to request a refund or cancellation, they must first confirm their identity. This is done by entering a token that was sent to the email address they provided when placing the order. This step ensures that only the rightful owner of the order can make changes or requests. o Identity Confirmation: Users check their email for a token and enter it on the Track Order page. This process verifies their identity and ensures that the request is secure. 2. Tour Purchases Page If users are on their Tour Purchases page (accessible via http://localhost:3000/account-settings?page=tour-purchases) and are authenticated, they can directly request a cancellation or refund without additional verification steps. o Direct Request: On this page, users can quickly send a request for cancellation or refund if the option is available. Request Status and Button Behavior  After Request Submission: Once a request for a cancellation or refund is submitted, the corresponding buttons on the interface will be:

o Blocked: The buttons become unclickable. o Greyed Out: The buttons are displayed in a disabled, greyed-out state. o Labeled “Requested”: The button text changes to “Requested” to indicate that the request has been made and is being processed. This approach ensures that users can only request refunds or cancellations securely and prevents multiple requests for the same order, maintaining a clear and orderly process. Order Statuses The Order Status field provides crucial information about the current state of an order. Here’s a detailed explanation of each status: 1. Booked This status indicates that the order has been successfully placed and the tickets are reserved. The user has completed the booking process, but the tour date might be in the future. 2. Scheduled The order is confirmed and the tour has been scheduled.
This status means that the tour is set for a specific date and time, and all arrangements are in place. 3. Cancelled The order has been cancelled, either by the user or due to other

circumstances. No further actions are required from the user, and a refund may be processed depending on the cancellation policy. 4. Ongoing The tour is currently in progress. The order status reflects that the event or tour is actively happening on the scheduled date. 5. Finished The tour has been completed. This status indicates that the event or tour has concluded, and no further actions are required from the user. 6. Pending The order is in a pending state, typically awaiting payment confirmation or additional processing.

This status means the order has been initiated but is not yet fully processed or confirmed. Each status provides users with a clear understanding of their order's progress, helping them manage their bookings effectively.

Tour Document Structure Here’s a detailed explanation of the fields and their purposes in the provided tour document: 1. _id o Type: ObjectId o Description: A unique identifier automatically generated by MongoDB for this document. 2.title o Type: String o Description: The name or title of the tour, e.g., "Explore the Eiffel Tower to the Fullest!" 3.overview o Type: String o Description: A brief description of the tour, providing a summary of what the tour entails. 4.country o Type: String o Description: The country where the tour takes place, e.g., "France." 5.city o Type: String o Description: The city where the tour is located, e.g., "Paris."

o Type: Integer o Description: The number of reviews for this tour. 7.views o Type: Integer o Description: The number of views this tour has received. 8.time o Type: Array of Strings o Description: Available times for the tour, e.g., ["6:30", "10:30", "14:30", "18:00"]. 9.type o Type: Array of Strings o Description: Types or categories of the tour, e.g., ["Nature Tours"]. 10. price o Type: Object o Description: Pricing information for different ticket categories and optional services.  adult: Price for adult tickets.
 youth: Price for youth tickets.  children: Price for children's tickets.  extra: Additional service costs.  servicePerBooking: Cost for adding a service per booking.

 servicePerPerson: Cost for adding a service per person.  adult: Additional cost per adult for extra services.  youth: Additional cost per youth for extra services. 11. tags o Type: Array of Strings o Description: Tags related to the tour for categorization and search filtering. Examples include "new", "popular", "price:0- 300", etc. 12. booked o Type: Integer o Description: The number of times this tour has been booked. 13. images o Type: Array of Strings o Description: URLs or paths to images related to the tour.

14. duration o Type: String o Description: The duration of the tour, e.g., "7 days." 15. groupSize o Type: Integer o Description: The maximum number of participants allowed in the tour group. 16. ages o Type: String

o Description: Age range of participants suitable for the tour, e.g., "6-99." 17. tourHighlights o Type: Array of Strings o Description: Key features or highlights of the tour. 18. whatsIncluded o Type: Object o Description: Lists what is included and not included in the tour price.  green: Included items like beverages, snorkeling equipment, etc.  orange: Not included items like tips, personal expenses, etc. 19. itinerary o Type: Array of Objects o Description: Detailed day-by-day itinerary of the tour.  title: The title of each day’s activity.

 description: Description of what happens on each day. 20. tourMap o Type: Array of Objects o Description: Map locations related to the tour with coordinates and labels.  label: Name or description of the location.  googleMap: Object containing Google Maps information.

 key: Identifier for the location.  location: Coordinates (latitude and longitude). 21. meetingPoint o Type: Object o Description: Location where the tour begins or where participants should meet.  title: Name of the meeting point.  location: Coordinates and location details. 22. searchIndex o Type: String o Description: Keywords or phrases used for search indexing to help users find this tour. 23. available o Type: Boolean o Description: Indicates if the tour is currently available for booking.

24. onSale o Type: Object o Description: Sale details if the tour is currently discounted.  newPrice: Discounted pricing for different ticket categories.  discountInPercentages: Percentage of discount applied. 25. languages o Type: Array of Strings

o Description: Languages available for the tour. 26. rating o Type: Object o Description: Ratings for various aspects of the tour.  overall: Overall rating.  location: Rating for the location.  amenities: Rating for amenities.  food: Rating for food.  price: Rating for price.  rooms: Rating for rooms.  tourOperator: Rating for the tour operator.

27. comments o Type: Array of ObjectIds o Description: References to comments or reviews related to this tour. This document structure provides a comprehensive view of all the details associated with a tour, including pricing, itinerary, highlights, and more. It allows for a rich and detailed representation of the tour offering in your application.
